## Replaceable tokens

| Token | Meaning |
|-------|---------|
| `<<REPO_NAME>>` | Repo short name. |
| `<<PACKAGE_NAME>>` | npm package name (e.g. `@os-eco/<<REPO_NAME>>-cli`). |
| `<<PRIMARY_BRANCH>>` | Default branch (almost always `main`). |
| `<<RELEASE_WORKFLOW>>` | Path to the release workflow YAML. |
| `<<TRACKER_PREFIX>>` | Repo-local tracker prefix (no trailing dash). |
| `<<CHANGELOG_PATH>>` | Path to the changelog (usually `CHANGELOG.md`). |
| `<<VERSION_SOURCES>>` | Files that must agree on the version (e.g. `package.json`, `src/index.ts`). |

## Scope

This runbook covers `<<REPO_NAME>>` operational procedures only:

1. Cutting a release.
2. Triaging a failed publish.
3. Rolling back a bad release.

For day-to-day development conventions, see `AGENTS.md`. For architecture,
see `docs/architecture-diagram.mmd` (if present) or the upstream
`SPEC.md` / `CLAUDE.md`.

## Pre-flight (do once per machine)

- `bun --version` ≥ the version in `package.json` `engines.bun`.
- `gh auth status` → authenticated, with `repo` + `workflow` scopes.
- `git remote -v` shows the canonical origin.
- For npm publish: `npm whoami` → publisher account; 2FA enabled.
- Local working tree on `<<PRIMARY_BRANCH>>`, fully up to date,
  `git status` clean.

## 1. Release procedure

Cut releases from `<<PRIMARY_BRANCH>>` only. Never tag a feature branch.

### 1.1 Decide the version

Follow [SemVer](https://semver.org). Pick:

- **MAJOR** for any backward-incompatible change to the public API
  (CLI flags removed, exported types renamed, breaking config schema).
- **MINOR** for new features or non-breaking additions.
- **PATCH** for bug fixes, doc-only changes, internal refactors.

`<<REPO_NAME>>` is pre-1.0 if `package.json` "version" starts with `0.`.
While pre-1.0, breaking changes go in MINOR; additive changes go in PATCH.

### 1.2 Update the version in every source of truth

`<<VERSION_SOURCES>>` must all agree. The release workflow fails the job
if they disagree.

```bash
# Example: package.json + src/index.ts (warren convention)
sed -i '' 's/"version": ".*"/"version": "X.Y.Z"/' package.json
# Then update VERSION constant manually if present.
```

Use `git diff` to confirm every version source moved to the new value.
Commit on its own:

```bash
git add <<VERSION_SOURCES>>
git commit -m "release: <<REPO_NAME>> X.Y.Z"
```

### 1.3 Update the changelog

`<<CHANGELOG_PATH>>` must have an entry for the new version at the top.

```markdown
## X.Y.Z — YYYY-MM-DD

### Added
- ...

### Changed
- ...

### Fixed
- ...
```

Group changes under standard headings (Added / Changed / Fixed /
Deprecated / Removed / Security). Link each entry to its
`<<TRACKER_PREFIX>>-XXXX` or `#NNN` if relevant. Commit:

```bash
git add <<CHANGELOG_PATH>>
git commit -m "release: changelog for X.Y.Z"
```

(Or squash both commits into one if your project prefers a single
release commit — be consistent across releases.)

### 1.4 Final gate check

```bash
bun install
bun run lint
bun run typecheck
bun test
bun run check:all
```

All four must exit 0. If any fails, **stop** — fix locally and re-run
before continuing.

### 1.5 Push to <<PRIMARY_BRANCH>>

```bash
git push origin <<PRIMARY_BRANCH>>
```

Pushing triggers `<<RELEASE_WORKFLOW>>`, which:

1. Re-runs the gate suite in CI.
2. Asserts every `<<VERSION_SOURCES>>` file agrees on `X.Y.Z`.
3. Builds + publishes `<<PACKAGE_NAME>>` to npm (if applicable).
4. Tags `vX.Y.Z` and creates a GitHub release with the
   `<<CHANGELOG_PATH>>` section as the body.

Watch the workflow run live:

```bash
gh run watch
```

### 1.6 Post-release sanity

After the workflow finishes:

```bash
git pull --tags
git tag --list | tail -5            # confirm vX.Y.Z is present
gh release view vX.Y.Z               # confirm release page renders
npm view <<PACKAGE_NAME>> version    # confirm the published version (if npm)
```

If `<<REPO_NAME>>` ships a CLI, smoke-install in a clean dir:

```bash
mkdir /tmp/<<REPO_NAME>>-smoke && cd /tmp/<<REPO_NAME>>-smoke
bun install <<PACKAGE_NAME>>
bunx <<PACKAGE_NAME>> --version
```

## 2. Triage of a failed publish

When `<<RELEASE_WORKFLOW>>` exits non-zero:

### 2.1 Read the log

```bash
gh run view --log-failed
```

Common failures and fixes:

| Symptom | Likely cause | Fix |
|---------|--------------|-----|
| `version mismatch` | `<<VERSION_SOURCES>>` disagree | Sync versions, push fix commit. |
| `npm publish ... 403` | Missing or expired `NPM_TOKEN` secret | Repository → Settings → Secrets → update `NPM_TOKEN`, re-run workflow. |
| `npm publish ... E409` | Version already published | Bump to the next patch; do **not** unpublish a live version. |
| `gh release create ... already exists` | Tag `vX.Y.Z` exists but a previous workflow created an incomplete release | Delete the orphan release in the GitHub UI, re-run the workflow. |
| `tsc` / `biome` / `bun test` failure | Local greens diverged from CI | Reproduce locally with `bun run check:all`; do **not** force-push to `<<PRIMARY_BRANCH>>`. |
| `gen:docs:check` / `gen:openapi:check` failure | Generated docs out of sync | `bun run gen:docs && bun run gen:openapi`; commit the diff. |

### 2.2 Re-run the workflow

After the fix commit lands on `<<PRIMARY_BRANCH>>`:

```bash
gh workflow run <<RELEASE_WORKFLOW>> --ref <<PRIMARY_BRANCH>>
```

Or push a no-op commit (`git commit --allow-empty -m "release: retry"`)
if the workflow only triggers on push.

### 2.3 If the publish half-succeeded

If npm publish completed but `gh release create` failed (or vice versa),
**do not unpublish**. Instead:

- Create the missing GitHub release manually:
  ```bash
  gh release create vX.Y.Z --notes-file <(awk '/^## X.Y.Z/,/^## /' <<CHANGELOG_PATH>>)
  ```
- Or, if npm has the version but the tag is missing:
  ```bash
  git tag vX.Y.Z
  git push origin vX.Y.Z
  ```

Record the deviation in `<<TRACKER_PREFIX>>-XXXX` so future operators
know the half-step happened.

## 3. Rollback

A "rollback" never means unpublishing. npm and git tags are immutable.
Rollback means **publishing a corrective version**.

### 3.1 Decide the severity

- **Critical** (data loss, security, total breakage): cut a new patch
  release reverting the change, in under 30 minutes.
- **High** (regression, broken feature on common path): cut a patch
  within the day.
- **Medium/Low**: fix forward on the next planned release.

### 3.2 Revert the offending commits

```bash
git checkout <<PRIMARY_BRANCH>>
git pull
git log --oneline -10
git revert <bad-sha>           # creates a new commit, preserves history
```

If the bad release is `X.Y.Z`, the revert commit goes into the work for
`X.Y.(Z+1)`.

### 3.3 Cut a follow-up release

Follow §1.1–§1.5. Note the rollback explicitly in
`<<CHANGELOG_PATH>>`:

```markdown
## X.Y.(Z+1) — YYYY-MM-DD

### Fixed
- Reverted <bad-commit-summary> from X.Y.Z which caused <symptom>.
  Tracking in <<TRACKER_PREFIX>>-XXXX.
```

### 3.4 Deprecate the bad version on npm

If `<<PACKAGE_NAME>>` is on npm and the bad version is dangerous:

```bash
npm deprecate <<PACKAGE_NAME>>@X.Y.Z "Critical bug; install X.Y.(Z+1) or later. See <<CHANGELOG_PATH>>."
```

`npm deprecate` does not remove the version (which would break
deterministic installs); it surfaces a warning at install time.

### 3.5 Communicate

- Update the GitHub release notes for `vX.Y.Z` with a banner:
  `> ⚠️ This release contains a regression. Use vX.Y.(Z+1) or later.`
- File `<<TRACKER_PREFIX>>-XXXX` with root cause + remediation links.
- If the project has a Discussions / changelog channel, post a short
  note linking to the corrective release.

## Appendix — Common commands

```bash
# Inspect recent releases
git tag --sort=-creatordate | head -5
gh release list --limit 5

# Inspect a failing workflow run
gh run list --workflow=<<RELEASE_WORKFLOW>> --limit 5
gh run view <run-id> --log-failed

# Re-run a single failed job
gh run rerun <run-id> --failed
```

## Appendix — Pre-publish checklist (copy-paste into release PR body)

- [ ] `<<VERSION_SOURCES>>` updated to X.Y.Z.
- [ ] `<<CHANGELOG_PATH>>` has a dated X.Y.Z section.
- [ ] `bun run check:all` exits 0 locally.
- [ ] `gh run watch` confirmed the release workflow succeeded.
- [ ] `npm view <<PACKAGE_NAME>> version` reports X.Y.Z (if npm).
- [ ] Smoke install in a clean dir succeeds.
- [ ] GitHub release page renders the changelog section correctly.
